<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>PUBLIC ADMINISTRATION SELECT COMMITTEE</title></head><body><div><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">PUB0004</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from Dr Tim Brown, Director, Centre for Comparative Housing Research (CCHR)</span></h1><h1 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></h1><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Background </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dr Tim Brown and his colleagues have been involved in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> consultancy and research projects on improving customer services for over 15 years. Their focus has been on housing, planning and regeneration including:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The development and evaluation of choice-based lettings in social housing; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Advisory and research ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">les on community land trusts (CLTs) and asset transfers; </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Working with councils and community groups on the impact of localism and the ‘big society’; and  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Lesson learning from other countries on public service reform.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dr Brown previously submitted writ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ten material and gave oral evidence to the Public Administration Select Committee Inquiry into choice, voice and public services in 2004/05.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Summary </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The long term reform of public services focuses on choice, empowerment and personalisation for individuals and communities. The benefits centre on capacity building as well as outcomes. However, it is a time-consuming and resource intensive process to deve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lop local innovative approaches to service delivery. There is, thus, a danger that radical models will remain at the margins rather than becoming part of the mainstream. One of the ways of addressing this challenge is to learn the lessons from other countr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ies.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question One </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">To what extent is the Government’s public service reform </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">programme</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">succeeding in:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a. Empowering citizens?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">b. Improving public services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">c. Ensuring that public services are accountable to the people</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">who use them, and to elected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">officials?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The current Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is a continuation of the work of previous administrations on putting the customer first in the design and delivery of public services. It represents a positive shift from the paternalistic ‘professionals know </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">best’ approach. The principles of empowerment, choice and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">personalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are the three key elements of a long term consensus that is also apparent in many other Western European countries. For the purpose of clarity, ‘empowerment’ relates to the provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of information so that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">user has the knowledge of what is on offer, by whom and how. ‘Choice’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on the opportunities for users to choose the content and level of service, the provider and form of access. ‘</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Personalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’  refers to the ability o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f the user to actively make informed decisions</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As public service reform is a long term project, it is difficult to evaluate the impact of the current government’s policies. Major changes take a long time to design and implement. For example, the previo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">us administration’s target set in 2002 that 100% of councils and their partners should be using choice-based lettings in social housing by the end of 2010 was achieved, as less than 5% failed to meet this requirement. In relation to community land trusts, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the previous Government’s Green Paper on Housing in 2007 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emphasised</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> their role. This has been further strengthened by this Government in its housing strategy in November 2011. In research that we undertook in 2012, we concluded that there was considerable </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">interest with over 150 active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. But outcomes in terms of new affordable homes and community-owned and managed facilities were limited. For example, less than 100 homes had so far been completed (see below). This was mainly because of the time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">required by communities to build up their skills and to go through the development process, which can be between 3-5 years.       </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Two </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What evidence is there that citizen-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">centred</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> approaches to public</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">service design, delivery and choice of provi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">der can deliver better</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">outcomes—ensuring not only better value for money, but also</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">greater social, economic and environmental value?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><h2 style="margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">Drawing on the research on choice-based lettings, the evidence is conclusive that customers like and want choice. We regul</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">arly found that over 75% of survey respondents preferred this method to traditional lettings schemes. This was because it was more straightforward, transparent and gave a greater say in the process to the user. However, customers have been unhappy with out</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">comes because of the lack of suitable social housing in the appropriate location – a case of ‘rearranging the deckchairs on the titanic’! During 2013, we acted as an advisor to the Office of the French Prime Minister on proposals for reforms of social hous</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">ing allocations and lettings. The same issue of inadequate supply of homes was a major concern to many of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:none"> involved in a three-month consultation exercise.  </span></h2><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In relation to community land trusts (CLTs) and similar initiatives, progress on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the development of specific projects since the Quirk Review on community asset disposals in 2007 has been slow. In a study of CLTs in 2012, we found that although there were over 150 active </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, less than 100 affordable homes had been completed.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Nevertheless a re-occurring theme from this and earlier research highlighted the benefits to communities and individuals in building up capacity, confidence, skills and trust. For example, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the development of a small CLT in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cumbria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> contributed to the abili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty of the local community to take over the ownership and management of the village pub, thus saving it from closure.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would conclude that while outcomes are vital, one should not ignore the benefits of the process for communities and individuals. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Three </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What are the risks and opportunities of opening up public services to</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">alternative forms of ownership, provision and accountability?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a. How do we ensure open access to public services under</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">alternative forms of ownership, provision and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">control?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In relation to community- based initiatives, our research over the last decade highlights the following three points on the process of community empowerment and service delivery:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Schemes fail to ‘get off the starting blocks’ because of a lack of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> capacity-building resources including skills and support. In the latter part of the last decade, there was interest in the transfer of assets by councils to local communities (following on from the Quirk Review). But schemes floundered because there were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">relatively few </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> able to facilitate initial action on the ground.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Failure of schemes to progress beyond the ideas stage. Many reasons appear to contribute to this state of affairs including unrealistic ambitions, community tensions, lack of ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ternal funding and a perceived rather than actual threat of the ‘red tape of bureaucracy’. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Long term community control and management can be a risk. As the population of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbourhood</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> changes, it can lead to a loss of effective local champions.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">From</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a government perspective, delivery can appear slow because of the time to build up community capacity and then design and implement schemes. There is no fast-track solution to this without disempowering communities by imposing external solutions to speed </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">up delivery. A balance, therefore, has to be achieved between speed and community empowerment. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Nevertheless, as has already been pointed out, the opportunities outweigh the risks in terms of building up the capacity of individuals and communities as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as outcomes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Four </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What are the challenges and opportunities in moving power away</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">from Whitehall and into the hands of citizens?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The fundamental issue is one of achieving a balance between local autonomy for councils and citizens and ensuring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a satisfactory standard of services. We need an open date on the extent to which we are prepared to have a ‘post code lottery’ with different levels and types of services in each area. Other Western European countries have well-established and different p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rinciples on central-local government relations. In the Netherlands, legislation tends to be facilitating rather than directive. For instance, there is a requirement to have a social housing allocations and lettings policy, but it is not prescriptive or de</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tailed. The Netherlands is the home of choice-based lettings. It was developed by the City of Delft as an advertising model in 1990. It is now widely used, but not every municipality has adopted this method. In addition, the Netherlands system of financing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local government relies on single pot funding rather than many different streams of ring-fenced financial support. Finally and most importantly, the local government culture is one of facilitating the provision of services through strategic commissioning </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rather than direct provision. There is, thus, a wide range of public, private and third sector providers. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is not to suggest that one should transfer the Dutch model to England, as the economic, political and social systems are different. However, instead, it can be used as a starting point for an informed debate about the relationships between citizens, c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ouncils and government.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Five </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How successful have the Government’s reforms been in opening up</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public services to grassroots community groups, rather than to large</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">private or third sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a. How can public service contracts be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">designed to enable service</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">users to choose from a wider range of providers, including</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">community-based providers, to achieve self-defined outcomes?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">b. What impact has the Community Right to Bid, Community Right</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to Challenge, and Community Right to Build had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> on local</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In relation to (a), the social value legislation that came into force in February 2013 requires public authorities to take into account the social and environmental issues in awarding contracts through the commissioning process. Thi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s might include, for instance, training and jobs for local people offered by a local social enterprise. However, we should be under no illusion that in a competitive market with private companies willing to make extremely low bids and public agencies faced</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with severe funding cuts, the prospects are not good. Indeed, despite broad Government support for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mutuals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, there is frequent coverage in the online ‘social enterprise UK’ of closures of companies. Nevertheless, examples such as Bristol and Plymouth that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have become the first social enterprise cities is an encouraging way forward in terms of setting a strategic agenda. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In relation to (b), as has already been pointed out, the localism initiatives on community rights are starting to have an impact on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neigh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bourhood</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> initiatives. But it will be a number of years before there are tangible outcomes. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More generally, there is much to commend about the government’s community rights approach including </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbourhood</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> planning. However, from our research on community</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> land trusts, there is a danger that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbourhoods</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in most need of such initiatives will be excluded. This is because of the lack of support from central and local government for socially excluded areas. For example, while there has been interest in u</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rban community land trusts, none so far have progressed to the development stage. Yet it is often inner city </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">neighbourhoods</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and peripheral social housing estates where there is a need for and the potential of grass-roots action. The Government has put in p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lace funding for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to provide support, but it is relatively insignificant and not targeted at areas that most require it.    </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Six </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How well do different tiers of government or different parts of single</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">central, local authority or district</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">councils level, work together to deliver public services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a. What impact does the Whitehall federal department structure</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">have on contracting for public services that fall across</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">departmental or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">organisational</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> boundaries</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">b. How does the Government ensure that public services develop</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the right kind of leadership as they become more open, more</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">subject to scrutiny and more customer-focused?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The relationship between central and local governments has been covered in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">response to question four. From a community and a user perspective, we would like to highlight that there is often bewilderment over the number and type of public agencies and public private partnerships involved in the design and delivery of services. We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">undertook a project in 2009 /10 in collaboration with Hull City Council on local delivery vehicles</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. We found that in East Hull, there were over 20 partnerships and local delivery vehicles. Residents welcomed the investment especially through the Goodwin T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rust (one of the largest social enterprises in the country), but were perplexed over ‘who was doing what’ and ‘whether it was co-</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ordinated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’. One of our recommendations was that the local authority should consider a broader facilitating and co-ordination ro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">le. This contributed to some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rationalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> over the plethora of delivery </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Seven </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What examples are there of innovative ways to deliver better public</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">services in local government, from other countries or from other</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public service</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> providers?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is value in exploring the design and delivery of public services in other countries. But it is essential to avoid simplistic policy transfer as the ‘grass is often not greener’ elsewhere! Instead we argue for lesson learning from other c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ountries so as to stimulate an informed debate on innovation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Four illustrations relevant to the material in this submission are: </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The French Government is passing enabling legislation (a Bill for access to housing and urban renovation) to allow local e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">xperimentation on social housing allocations and lettings. This is resulting in the likely development of new ideas in cities such as Grenoble and Lyon, based loosely on some elements of our system of choice-based lettings. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Dutch government has previ</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ously funded an independent social housing experiment unit (SEV) that worked with municipalities and communities to test innovative solutions that were then robustly evaluated before they were rolled out more widely. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the USA, grass roots </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> have been a feature of urban and rural regeneration e.g. community development corporations and large community land trusts. Learning the lessons from these schemes would be valuable for our community rights approach. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In a number of Western European cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ntries, initiatives such as housing co-operatives and self-build are significant in tackling housing supply issues and achieving community engagement. In England, although there has been discussion of these types of approaches for at least a decade as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as small-scale government support, they remain marginal. A key issue is whether and how can these be moved into the mainstream? </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have already made reference to other Dutch examples in our response to question four. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There are two interrelated and imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ortant points arising from these illustrations. Firstly, governments can foster innovation through facilitating legislation. Secondly, grass-roots </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> can flourish and grow but they need local and national support.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Eight </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">realistic is it that “choice” can be exercised in public service</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">provision or should we be looking instead at greater control by users</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">so they can ensure that public services become more responsive to</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">changing needs?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a. How do we make sure that all citizen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s are able to influence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The example of choice-based lettings illustrates the importance of choice. But it cannot be separated from empowerment and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">personalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. Customers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are only empowered if they are provided with advice and information on the realistic choices that are avai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lable. There are too many cases where, for example, housing advice services are not integrated with lettings. Similarly, we have come across examples where vulnerable households have been set up to fail, as support has not been available to help them make </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">informed decisions. This is especially as </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">personalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> requires that the customers can make informed decisions on their individual unique requirements. The choice agenda has to engage with that of equality and diversity. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, the prospects for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> choice, empowerment and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">personalisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are uncertain in the current public sector financial climate – they are at a tipping point. There could, firstly, be a service retrenchment leading to reduced eligibility for services. In this case, choice would be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">extremely limited in terms of scope and availability. Secondly, there might be a return to a traditional paternalistic model. Thirdly, and more optimistically, fiscal austerity might lead to a radical rethink that promotes mutualism. There are examples of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the latter taking place . </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rochdale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Boroughwide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Housing, for instance, has taken over the ownership and management of over 13,000 council homes. It is a mutual </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> wholly owned by tenants and employees. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Nine </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What safeguards should be i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n place to deal with service providers</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">who fail to deliver services, or who deliver services of an insufficient</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">quality?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Reactive responses to service failure are an essential requirement. The starting point has to be an effective in-house system. Neverth</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eless, there has to be external regulation. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our work in Hull highlighted that residents felt that it was the role of the local authority to call local delivery vehicles and public private partnerships to account. In fact, this type of approach is common </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the Netherlands. Nevertheless, it is not appropriate where the council runs local services.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Ten </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How do we ensure that best practice is shared so it can be replicated</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in the context of greater diversity of provision?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a. Are there any types </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of public services that you think should not</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">be opened up to new models of design, delivery or provision?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The basic issue is that many case studies are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">labelled</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as best practice without any transparent evidence. Websites and reports frequently cite good practice, but it is far from clear how and why they have been selected. In our opinion, they have to be robu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">stly and independently evaluated on process and outcomes before being accredited as best practice. There are lessons to be learnt from the Dutch example of the work of the social housing experiment unit (SEV) – see above. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><h3 style="font-weight:normal; margin:0pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Eleven </span></h3><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How well has t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he system of Payment by Results worked in the</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">delivery of public services and how do we make it work better?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are unable to make a response to this question.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Question Twelve </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What progress has been made in setting up </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mutuals</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> as an effective</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">way of d</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">elivering public services?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We have used above the example of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rochdale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Boroughwide</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Housing. It illustrates similar issues to the slow growth of community land trusts and community rights. Firstly, it takes time and resources to develop and deliver innovati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ve approaches to public services. Secondly, active community and employee involvement is not straightforward. There is often initial </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">scepticism</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and cynicism over such initiatives. These cannot be quickly overcome. Thirdly, while the legislative and regulat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ory environments are not necessarily obstacles, they nonetheless have to be addressed. Progress, therefore, can appear to be slow and protracted. But this is the inevitable part of developing radical innovative solutions. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:left;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">1</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> There is a fuller discussion of these definitions in Brown, T. and Yates, N. (2011) Choice, Empowerment and Personalisation: Taking Forward Public Services in a Reces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">sion?. In Richardson, J. (Ed) (2011) From Recession to Renewal, Bristol, Policy Press pp 157-178.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> Brown, T. and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">Lishman</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">, R. (2010) Co-ordinating Regeneration: Improving Effectiveness in Local Delivery, Newcastle, Northern Way, Regeneration Momentum Resea</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">rch Paper 3.   </span></p></body></html>